🚀 What is Express.js?

Express.js is a lightweight web framework built on top of Node.js.

It helps you build web servers and APIs faster by handling repetitive tasks like:

Routing
Request/response handling
Middleware management


🤔 Why Express Simplifies Node.js Development

Using raw Node.js means working directly with the built-in http module—which gets messy quickly.

Raw Node.js Example
const http = require('http');

http.createServer((req, res) => {
  if (req.url === '/' && req.method === 'GET') {
    res.end('Home Page');
  }
}).listen(3000);

You must:
Manually check URL and method

http.createServer((req, res) => {
  console.log(req.url);    // "/about"
  console.log(req.method); // "GET"
});
if (req.url === '/' && req.method === 'GET') {
  res.end('Home');
} else if (req.url === '/about' && req.method === 'GET') {
  res.end('About');
} else if (req.url === '/login' && req.method === 'POST') {
  res.end('Login');
}


in express - app.get('/')
app.post('/login')


Handle headers yourself

res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' });
res.end(JSON.stringify({ message: 'Hello' }));
let body = '';

req.on('data', chunk => {
  body += chunk;
});

req.on('end', () => {
  const parsed = JSON.parse(body);
  console.log(parsed);
});
In express
app.use(express.json());

app.post('/data', (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.body); // already parsed
  res.json({ message: 'Hello' });
});

Repeat logic for every route


